<br>
The cast times you omitted are important because there is one major difference between extending the fight and shortening the fight.<br>
<br>
Heals buy YOU time, which you can use to do something else(like nuke), while nukes only take away time from the mob.  Also, the more time your pet is in combat, the more damage he'll do.  Intuition has told me that the usual result for a specific encounter is more favorable using the pet heal, if the mob has a high DPS.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The higher the mob DPS, the less appealing pet heals are compared to nukes.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->What this fails to take into consideration is that the higher a mob's dps, the less time you will have to nuke.  The fight becomes limited by how many hitpoints your pet has.  -if- you could keep your pet healed indefinitely and keep the fight stable, you will only lose if you run out of mana.<br>
<br>
Lets take an imaginary example.<br>
<br>
Pet Health 4000<br>
Pet DPS 60<br>
Mob DPS 100<br>
Mob HP 12000<br>
<br>
The mob will kill your pet in 40 seconds flat if you don't heal it.  You have enough time to squeeze in 6 full casts of sofb, and maybe, if you're really really good, one cast Char.  At 100% effectiveness(nuke bonus+resists), you'll do 9140 damage.  Not enough to kill the mob before it kills your pet.  (Also note that this is almost 230dps nuking, which I have found rather hard to achieve in actual combat.  100-130 is usually closer to maximum.)  The pet heal TEI is 580 every 12.5 seconds.  This is a raw 46dps healed.<br>
<br>
So now you have<br>
Pet Health:  4000<br>
Pet DPS 60<br>
Mob DPS 100 minus 46 healed per sec = 54 dps<br>
Mob Health: 12000<br>
<br>
This time, it will take the mob 74 seconds to kill the pet.  Pet damage goes up, but only to 4440, still not enough to win, indeed it seems less effective this way.  However, consider two possibilities.<br>
<br>
First, that with a faster heal, or a heal to chain in between, you could make the fight last even longer.  Consider the level 60 heal..  900 damage every 14.5 seconds, but you can add 580 in the meantime.  This comes out to 102 healed damage per second..  Given that, Mob DPS doesn't mean anything.  You can just make the fight last until your pet deals 9400 damage.  It becomes a question of your mana pool and how much mana you are spending on heals.  Mana is not necessarily an issue in a burn-down fight.<br>
<br>
If you don't have the 60 heal, you can, instead, chain nukes in between heals.<br>
<br>
Since we were very generous with the burn-down example, I'll assume that the mage can fit in exactly 1 SOFB during the recast of TEI.<br>
<br>
Pet Health:  4000<br>
Pet DPS 60<br>
Mob DPS 54<br>
Mob Health: 12000<br>
<br>
Fight lasts 75 seconds, during which time you have time for 5 SOFB.<br>
<br>
Pet damage over 75 seconds = 4500<br>
Nuke damage over 75 seconds = 5025<br>
<br>
Total damage = <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  9525</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Total damage using straight burn-down = <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  9140</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
If the mob hitpoints had been in this range, the encounter may have been winnable with heal/nuke alternation but not straight nuking.  The second strategy is more mana dependant, and usually close to as mana intensive as burn-down.<br>
<br>
Note that I've done a little heal parsing, here: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub6.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showMessage?topicID=660.topic">In Combat pet regen test</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
I will try to parse a fight where I alternate nukes/heals to get some real numbers, rather than theoretical ones.<br>
<br>
