<br>
I went for the simpler model, well because it was simpler, and it factored out hit points on both sides of the equation, leaving me only with seconds and DPS.<br>
<br>
As an aside for later elaboration, it turned out that a strong measure of a mob or pet was:<br>
<br>
Power = HP * DPS<br>
<br>
Which had some interesting consequences.  But like I said, I factored out HP because it was simpler and clearer.  By factoring out hitpoints, as you point out, the model assumes that there is enough time to intervene.  I should have remembered from physics that when you factor something out like that, you need to look at it again later to see if the assumptions that you made in order to factor it out in fact hold.<br>
<br>
But I just re-worked the model, as you suggested, and, as you suggested, an important difference between nukes and heals is that heals can buy you the time to nuke, but nukes cannot buy you time to nuke or heal.<br>
<br>
For sustaining pets, the nuke/heal, nuke/heal alternation is most commonly seen.  In fact, chaining heals is rarely seen except againt low DPS (under 30 DPS) mobs like shrooms, or with archmages with the rare 60 heal against mobs where aggro must be avoided at all costs, such as Yeldema.<br>
<br>
I will think about this some more, and try to establish when the simpler model holds, and when it breaks down, and what that says.<br>
<br>
But it does suggest that heals are better than the first model says.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Itsastony:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Like they are designed they were never meant to heal our pet completly. Just a portion of its health, to keep it alive a bit longer for those situations where a fight is close. Using a pet heal then shifts the balance and helps you to try being able to win.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That is how mages use those spells, and exactly how it seems to be.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Pet x costs zzzmana<br>
<br>
Pet x 50% heal (should)=1/2 zzzmana<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>way</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> too good a ratio.  It would give healers <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>all</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> of the advantages of chaining pets, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>none</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> of the disadvantages of chaining, and would be substantially better than chaining.  It would be over powering.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Calebe:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Pet heals as they stand now are not effiecent, and as shown by Gladius are not worth using.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Please do not take my disagreements with your statements personally, they are never intended as such.  They are meant to clarify and well disagree.  I don't take it personally when you disagree with me.<br>
<br>
No, this is not what <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Goladus</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> shows.  What he shows is that heals, unlike nukes, buy additional fighting time, which can then be used to heal or nuke.  Exactly how to evaluate this yet is not entirely clear, but it means that heals are not as bad as my simple model implies.  Even if they were as bad as my first model says, the fact remains that you cannot chain nuke in practice because you would get aggro.  Heals do not get aggro, and give time for the aggro from nukes to die down.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Goladus</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> shows additionally that heals buy time to cast another spell.<br>
<br>
Not to argue with you further at the moment, but one thing you are mistaken about chaining that might change your evaluation of the merits of this technique.  One generally does not dismiss or reclaim the pet, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>then</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> begin casting the next one.  As you point out, that is impractical without root.  Instead, one begins casting the new pet as the old pet is dying, and then typing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /pet get lost</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or press the GO AWAY button on the PET INFO window just before the new pet finishes casting, so that old pet disappears just a second or two before the new one appears.<br>
<br>
Also, please keep in mind that even though I remain unconvinced of the need for a better pet heal, I do realize that <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>now</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> is the last time to ask for long time, and I have started another thread for that very purpose, so that those mages who want a better heal can make and compare proposals.  I both chain and sustain pets as appropriate, and I use the existing 52 pet heal.<br>
<br>
Strong as I may argue my positions and dissect the arguments of those I disagree with, I do not mistake my opinions for that of the mage community, nor do I long forget my duty as a moderator to facilitate the needs of the large mage community.<br>
<br>
The purpose of this thread is to develop some kind of rational context for evaluating heals.<br>
<br>
