<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I will think about this some more, and try to establish when the simpler model holds, and when it breaks down, and what that says.<br>
<br>
But it does suggest that heals are better than the first model says.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Just thinking briefly without going into numbers..<br>
<br>
The simple model is correct in its conclusion that nukes mean more against mobs with a higher damage output.  Since a nuke shortens the amount of time a mob has to deal damage, nukes will reduce more damage from more powerful mobs.  However, this effect is meaningless if the length of the fight is already determined by the health of the pet.  Anything up to the critical point where you &quot;close the gap&quot; is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>necessary</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> to even win.<br>
<br>
If the gap is to be entirely closed by nukes, you can measure the nuke DPS you <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>need</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> to achieve in order to win.  As a mobs hp -or- dps go up, the nuking DPS you need to kill the mob increases linearly.  (hp and dps is probably quadratic or something I don't have my pen/paper handy at the moment hehe).  Pet dps would be a mitigating factor..  As pet dps went up nuke dps would go down linearly.  Same with pet hitpoints.<br>
<br>
ok I guess I have time for a few quick numbers<br>
<br>
*estimates* from that log with the icewell sentinel (51+ mob, was summmoning my pet, immune or highly resistant to procs to ) are<br>
<br>
mob dps 54<br>
pet dps with ds 72<br>
pet health 3890 (from other tests)<br>
mob health 14000<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre> 
(mob health) - (mob dps/pet health) * (pet dps)
-----------------------------------------------
                 (mob dps/pet health)
</pre><!--EZCODE CODE END--><br>
<br>
You'll find out what your nuke dps needs to be.<br>
<br>
For the Icewell Sentinel(estimate), I would need to nuke at 117 dps <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>to tie</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->... to kill him as he kills my pet.<br>
<br>
117dps is possible for a mage..<br>
<br>
But on that fight, not without drawing aggro.<br>
<br>
Also, if you increase the numbers just a tad.. say, a mob with 60dps and 20k hitpoints, you'd need 228 dps, which is probably getting really close to the current hard cap on single target spell damage output.<br>
<br>
For a 32k mob that deals 70ish dps you'll need to nuke for about 500, if your pet can keep up 72.  It actually might be more beneficial to think of this in terms of &quot;extra damage,&quot; not just nuke damage.  A mage <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>might</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> be able to deal 250 dps, which leaves 250 for others.  <br>
<br>
On the other hand, if you can heal 35 dps against that 32k, 72 dps mob, you'll only need about 220 extra dps.  If you can also add some nukes at 40 dps, the difference is now only 180, which can probably be filled easily by any two other casters.  <br>
<br>
This method will break down when the dps averages mean less than cast times.  For increasingly short fights, the nuke dps and heal dps will be exremely spikey.<br>
<br>
closing thoughts..<br>
<br>
Giving a mage more ability to deal damage increases his worth in most situations...  Giving a mage better heals only matters when his pet is taking damage.  In the isolated solo example, it may make more sense to increase nuking power than healing power.  However, that seems less favorable as you think about other areas of the game where a magician might start stepping on other class toes(like wizards).<br>
<br>
Increasing pet heals too much would, imo, be really unfair to warriors.  Mages could become better at holding mobs at bay than warriors, (funny melee range rule excepted).<br>
<br>
However, balancing the power of both could increase the power of the mage overall <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>without</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> going too far in one direction, changing the class definition and porbably crossing other class boundaries. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ucalebe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Calebe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 391<br> <font color=#333333>(10/4/02 1:56:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Model for evaluating utility of mage pet heals</span><hr size=1> I always find it amusing when a magician says we may cross &quot;Class Boundaries&quot;.<br>
