<br>
As for class boundaries, well I agree that class boundaries are becoming less distinct, and I for one do not like it at all.  What is the point of being any one particular class, if all classes have effectively the same abilities?<br>
<br>
How can we argue that one proposed solution is more appropriate for mages than another proposal except in the context of class boundaries?<br>
<br>
Class envy, the argument <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Class A has X, therefore we should have X&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a viscious cycle, one that sadly we find ourselves in.  Each time class envy is accepted and acted upon, the class boundaries weaken further.  The weaker class boundaries are, the less compelling arguments based on class capabilities are, and the more compelling class envy becomes.<br>
<br>
For example, suppose mages get a pet heal comparable or even better to the best beastlord pet heal.  Beastlords are now in a stronger position to ask for increased HP for their warders.  If strong heals were previously seen as compensating for low hitpoints, that argument is much less compelling if mages have strong heals.  If beastlords ask for and receive a major hitpoint increase, then some mages are going to start asking for beastlord pet buffs, the proc for example.  Since beastlord warders have become more similar to elementals, the class boundaries have been blurred, and it is harder to argue that mages are not entitled to beastlord procs.<br>
<br>
Carried to the extreme, if beastlord pets then become the functional equals of elementals, then in order to balance the classes, beastlords might well demand stronger nukes and then mages more ability to survive combat, until beastlords and mages are hardly distinguishable.<br>
<br>
Class boundaries are important, and yes, I will fight to preserve them.  Even if the trend is against them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
